1 Rationale

As observed during the biological QA, there is a bias in the expression measurements. As the samples go inward the wood, less genes are expressed (presumably because of lower amount of materials leading to an overall lower sequencing depth), which was over-compsensated by the library size correction, resulting in an average increase of gene expression across sections from the phloem to the xylem.

3 Correction

Split data in expression bins (10 of 10% each)

v <- apply(vst,2,function(co){split(co,cut(co,10))})

There is clearly a linear relationship in every bin. Also, albeit less apparent, the log fold change range of the bins increase with the bin average expression

dev.null <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  boxplot(lapply(v,"[[",i),las=2,names=nams)}
)

Model the relationship for the three datasets, per bin

lms <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  x1 <- 1:9
  x2 <- x3 <- 1:12
  y1 <- sapply(lapply(v,"[[",i),median)[1:9]
  y2 <- sapply(lapply(v,"[[",i),median)[10:21]
  y3 <- sapply(lapply(v,"[[",i),median)[22:33]
  l1 <- lm(y1~x1)
  l2 <- lm(y2~x2)
  l3 <- lm(y3~x3)
  return(c(l1$coefficients["x1"],
           l2$coefficients["x2"],
           l3$coefficients["x3"]))
})

dimnames(lms) <- list(levels(samples$Tree),sprintf("Bin%02d",1:10))

3.1 Corrected matrix

c.vst <- do.call(cbind,lapply(1:nlevels(samples$Tree),function(i,dat,smpl,preds){
  
  # get the data
  sel <- smpl$Tree==levels(smpl$Tree)[i]
  d <- dat[,sel]
  
  # create a correction matrix
  mat <- matrix(1,nrow=nrow(d),ncol=ncol(d))
  
  # predict the effect  
  res <- sapply(1:ncol(d),function(i,p){
    predict(p,data.frame(x=dat[,i]))
  },preds[[i]])
  
  mat <- mat * (1 + res)
  
  boxplot(mat,names=nams[sel])
  
  # apply the correction
  d * (1 / mat)
  
},vst,samples,list(l1,l2,l3)))

3.1.2 Bins

Bin the corrected expression

n.c <- apply(c.vst,2,function(co){split(co,cut(co,10))})

And compare it to the non corrected one

The correction clearly had an effect, but it did not correct fully the observed effect, presumably because some of it is of biological origin. It is presumable than massive transcriptomic rearrangements occur betwen the cambium and the two derived tissues, phloem and xylem.

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
dev.null <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
  boxplot(lapply(n.c,"[[",i),las=2,names=nams,cex.axis=0.6)
  boxplot(lapply(v,"[[",i),las=2,names=nams,cex.axis=0.6)
})

n.lms <- sapply(1:10,function(i){
